## A Simple, Crash-Proof Workflow
Follow these steps to keep things clean and stable.

Step 1: Develop Your AI Flow in Isolation
Navigate into your ai-functions directory: cd ai-functions.

Define your flow in src/index.ts. Start with something incredibly simple to make sure the plumbing works.

TypeScript

// In ai-functions/src/index.ts
import { defineFlow, runFlow } from '@genkit-ai/flow';
import * as z from 'zod';

export const myFirstFlow = defineFlow(
  {
    name: 'myFirstFlow',
    inputSchema: z.string(),
    outputSchema: z.string(),
  },
  async (prompt) => {
    return `You sent me this: ${prompt}. It works!`;
  }
);
Test it with the Genkit UI. This is the most important step! Run genkit start in your terminal. This launches a local web page where you can test myFirstFlow without needing your main app at all. This proves your AI logic works on its own.

Step 2: Deploy Your AI as a Cloud Function
Once you're happy with your flow in the Genkit UI, deploy it.

Make sure your flow is "exposed" as an HTTPS callable function. In Genkit, this is often handled by default when deploying to Firebase.

From the ai-functions directory, run: firebase deploy --only functions.

This uploads your AI flow to Google's servers and gives you a secure endpoint (a URL) to call it.

Step 3: Call the AI from Your Main App
Now, go into your app directory: cd ../app.

In your application code, use the Firebase client SDK to call the function you just deployed.

JavaScript

// In your app's JavaScript/TypeScript file
import { getFunctions, httpsCallable } from "firebase/functions";

const functions = getFunctions();
const callMyFirstFlow = httpsCallable(functions, 'myFirstFlow');

async function askAI(promptText) {
  try {
    const result = await callMyFirstFlow(promptText);
    console.log("AI Response:", result.data); // result.data will be "You sent me this: [promptText]. It works!"
    return result.data;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Error calling AI function:", error);
    // Show an error message to the user
  }
}

// Example usage
askAI("Hello from my urban research app!");
Now your app can talk to your AI without containing any of the complex Genkit code. If you need to update the AI's "brain," you just work inside the ai-functions folder and redeploy. Your main app doesn't need to change at all.

