The firebase deploy command is failing with an ENOENT error because it cannot find a package.json in a functions directory. This is because our project is a monolithic Next.js application where all code is managed by the top-level package.json.
Please apply the following comprehensive fix to the firebase.json file to align it with our project's architecture.
Action:
Open the file firebase.json in the root of the project.
Replace the entire content of this file with the following new, corrected version.
This new version does two critical things:
It removes the incorrect functions block that was causing the error.
It correctly configures hosting to use the Next.js integration, which will automatically handle the deployment of your API routes as Cloud Functions.
code
JSON
{
  "firestore": {
    "rules": "firestore.rules",
    "indexes": "firestore.indexes.json"
  },
  "storage": {
    "rules": "storage.rules"
  },
  "hosting": {
    "source": ".",
    "ignore": [
      "firebase.json",
      "**/.*",
      "**/node_modules/**"
    ],
    "frameworksBackend": {
      "region": "us-central1"
    }
  }
}
Reasoning:
For a modern Next.js application deployed to Firebase, you do not need a separate functions block in your firebase.json. The hosting configuration, with a source of . and a frameworksBackend block, tells Firebase that this is a full-stack web framework. Firebase will then automatically build your application and deploy any API routes (like /api/harmonize and /api/rag) as the necessary Cloud Functions for you. This is the correct, modern configuration for your monolithic architecture and will resolve the deployment error.
Please apply this definitive fix.

